Act/Order.text: Delimitation of Parliamentary and Assembly Constituencies Order, 1951[7]

Explanation.text: The Indian Constitution came into effect and new constituencies were created.
A re-organised Madhya Pradesh was formed by merging the former states of Madhya Pradesh, Madhya Bharat, Vindhya Pradesh and Bhopal.

Act/Order.text: Delimitation of Parliamentary and Assembly Constituencies Order, 1961[12]

Explanation.text: There were changes in the number and reservation status of constituencies. Two-member constituencies were abolished.

Act/Order.text: Delimitation of Parliamentary and Assembly Constituencies Order, 1976[15]

Explanation.text: There were changes in the number and reservation status of constituencies.

The new state of Chhattisgarh was created from the eastern parts of Madhya Pradesh.[22]

There were 320 assembly constituencies in undivided Madhya Pradesh. After the split, 230 of them composed the reduced legislative assembly of the state.
There were changes in the reservation status and area covered by constituencies.

Effect.text: Assam state's Mizo hills area was converted into the separate Union Territory of Mizoram.
Mizoram was given full statehood after the Mizoram Peace Accord, and the number of seats in the legislative assembly was increased to 40.
There was an increase in the number of seats reserved for Scheduled Tribes.

Act/Order.text: Delimitation of Parliamentary and Assembly Constituencies Order, 2008

Effect.text: There were changes in the reservation status and area covered by constituencies.[20]

Details.text: Elections announced for a new State Council with 12 (out of 18) elected members

Representation of Sikkim Subjects Regulation, 1966[4]
Constituencies increased to 5, 2 additional general seats added

The Government of Sikkim Act, 1974[5]
Multi-seat constituencies eliminated

Effect.text: The legislative assembly was created with 30 elected seats.[11]
Tripura was converted from a Union Territory to a state. The size of the assembly was increased to 60.
